CRISPR dependency analysis summary for ds001_depmap

I analyzed 50,000 cell-line records with ten dependency outcomes. Dependency scores are interpreted so more negative values indicate stronger dependency.

The initial oncogene-dependency checks were strongly supported. BRAF V600E cell lines were much more BRAF-dependent than BRAF-wild-type lines (mean dependency_BRAF -0.8047 versus -0.2495; effect -0.5552; p<1e-300). EGFR-amplified lines were more EGFR-dependent (effect -0.3486; p<1e-300), ERBB2-amplified lines were more ERBB2-dependent (effect -0.4321; p<1e-300), and KRAS-mutant lines were more KRAS-dependent (effect -0.3075; p<1e-300). NF1 loss also marked a smaller but clear RIT1 dependency shift (effect -0.0955; p<1e-300).

I then tested screen and proliferation-associated patterns. Faster-growing cell lines had substantially more negative POLR2A dependency, especially above the 75th percentile of growth_rate_doublings_per_day (effect -0.1043; p<1e-300) and above the 90th percentile (effect -0.1211; p<1e-300). TMED10 showed a weaker pattern tied mainly to growth and Cas9 activity: high-growth lines had mean dependency_TMED10 -0.2816 versus -0.2447 in the complement (effect -0.0369; p<1e-300), and the high-growth/high-Cas9 subgroup sharpened this to effect -0.0605 (p=3.6e-9). I did not find a strong coherent lineage or genomic-feature subgroup for TMED10.

MYC/8q24-related features were associated with DHX9 and RPL11 dependencies. Higher rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm was associated with more negative dependency_DHX9 (slope -0.0161; p<1e-300), and the high-growth/MYC-high subgroup had mean dependency_DHX9 -0.3892 versus -0.3297 (effect -0.0595; p<1e-300). RPL11 dependency tracked 8q24/MYC status: high copy_number_8q24 had effect -0.0988 (p<1e-300), MYC amplification had effect -0.1091 (p<1e-300), and the combined high-8q24/MYC-amplified subgroup had effect -0.1123 (p<1e-300).

The strongest heterogeneous dependency was KIF18A. Colorectal lineage alone had a large shift in dependency_KIF18A (mean -0.7204 versus -0.2524; effect -0.4680; p<1e-300). APC mutation and high WNT activity also pointed to the same biology: apc_mutation=1 had effect -0.2921, and wnt_activity_score>=1.427 had effect -0.3773. Systematic subgroup search refined this to colorectal, WNT-active, SMAD4-intact cell lines. The colorectal/WNT90/SMAD4-intact subgroup had mean dependency_KIF18A -1.2409 versus -0.2677 in the complement (effect -0.9733; p<1e-300). Within colorectal WNT90 lines, SMAD4-intact lines were much more KIF18A-dependent than SMAD4-loss lines (effect -0.9767; p<1e-300), showing that SMAD4 loss suppresses or disables the dependency signal.

The final best-supported buried subgroup was: lineage='colorectal', apc_mutation=1, wnt_activity_score>=0.819, smad4_loss=0, and rnaseq_ASCL2_log2_tpm>=3.559. This subgroup had mean dependency_KIF18A -1.3320 (n=1511) versus -0.2749 in all other lines (effect -1.0572; p<1e-300). In colorectal/APC-mutant/WNT75 lines, SMAD4-intact cases had mean -1.2990 versus -0.2557 for SMAD4-loss cases (effect -1.0433; p<1e-300), supporting the complete subgroup definition and identifying SMAD4 loss as a suppressive predicate.

Overall, the dataset contains expected direct oncogene dependency signals for BRAF, EGFR, ERBB2, KRAS, and RIT1; proliferation/screen-quality associations for POLR2A and TMED10; MYC/8q24-associated DHX9 and RPL11 dependencies; and one prominent buried interaction in KIF18A centered on colorectal APC/WNT activity that is enabled by intact SMAD4 and further enriched by ASCL2 expression.

 succeeded in 10517ms:
CRISPR dependency analysis summary for ds001_depmap

Dataset and approach
I analyzed 50000 cell-line records with molecular features, screen covariates, and 10 dependency outcomes. Dependency scores are interpreted on their natural scale, where more negative values indicate stronger dependency after knockout. I tested main effects, subgroup contrasts, and adjusted linear models. P-values are large-sample normal approximations from Welch contrasts or OLS coefficient tests.

Iteration 1: canonical oncogene dependency checks
The expected matched driver dependencies were strongly supported. BRAF V600E cell lines had more negative dependency_BRAF scores than BRAF-wild-type lines (mean -0.805 vs -0.250; effect -0.555; p<1e-300). EGFR-amplified lines had more negative dependency_EGFR scores (mean -0.601 vs -0.252; effect -0.349; p<1e-300). ERBB2-amplified lines had more negative dependency_ERBB2 scores (mean -0.686 vs -0.253; effect -0.432; p<1e-300). KRAS-mutant lines had more negative dependency_KRAS scores (mean -0.559 vs -0.252; effect -0.307; p<1e-300).

Iteration 2: additional driver-context dependencies
NF1 loss was associated with stronger RIT1 dependency (mean -0.353 vs -0.257; effect -0.096; p=2.03e-70). A MYC/8q24 context was associated with stronger RPL11 dependency: MYC-amplified high-copy_number_8q24 lines had mean dependency_RPL11 -0.365 vs -0.252 in the complement (effect -0.112; p=3.53e-148). MYC amplification had a much smaller but significant association with dependency_DHX9 (effect -0.018; p=1.68e-05).

Iterations 3-4: KIF18A heterogeneity and refinement
KIF18A showed the clearest noncanonical subgroup effect. Colorectal lineage alone was associated with much more negative dependency_KIF18A (mean -0.720 vs -0.252; effect -0.468; p<1e-300). APC mutation also had a large negative effect (mean -0.545 vs -0.253; effect -0.292; p<1e-300), and high WNT activity was directionally consistent (effect -0.217; p<1e-300). The complete subgroup, lineage == colorectal, apc_mutation == 1, and wnt_activity_score >= 0.819, was far stronger than any component alone: mean dependency_KIF18A -1.112 vs -0.253; effect -0.859; p<1e-300; n=3133. Within colorectal APC-mutant lines, high WNT further separated KIF18A dependency (effect -0.839; p<1e-300). Among high-WNT lines, the full colorectal/APC-mutant context was still much more dependent than high-WNT lines outside that context (effect -0.857; p<1e-300). This supports a complete subgroup definition rather than WNT activity alone.

Iteration 5: growth and screen-context effects
Fast-growing lines were more dependent on several broadly essential processes. Lines with growth_rate_doublings_per_day >= 0.964 had more negative dependency_POLR2A (effect -0.104; p=4.27e-183), dependency_TMED10 (effect -0.037; p=2.22e-24), and dependency_DHX9 (effect -0.037; p=1.50e-24). Continuous models also showed negative growth-rate slopes for POLR2A (-0.305 per doubling/day), TMED10 (-0.101), and DHX9 (-0.109).

Iterations 6-7: systematic dependency-heterogeneity search
I screened feature-defined subgroups for every dependency outcome. For BRAF, the dominant signal remained braf_v600e, with the high-growth BRAF V600E subgroup showing mean dependency_BRAF -0.829. For EGFR, the best exploratory subgroup combined egfr_amplification, high growth, and high copy_number_8q24 (effect -0.391; p=1.27e-71). For ERBB2, an ERBB2-amplified breast/high-IFN subgroup was most negative (effect -0.467; p=9.53e-108). For KRAS, KRAS-mutant high-growth STK11-loss lines were strongly dependent, although the simpler KRAS-mutant contrast remained the main supported relationship. For RIT1, NF1-loss with low aneuploidy and low mutation burden was the most negative exploratory subgroup. For KIF18A, the colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT subgroup was by far the strongest subgroup across the entire scan. TMED10 and DHX9 had only modest exploratory subgroup hits, while POLR2A and RPL11 were most consistent with growth and MYC-context effects respectively.

Iterations 8-9: adjusted models
The canonical driver effects persisted after adjusting for growth_rate_doublings_per_day, cas9_activity_score, and lineage: adjusted coefficients were BRAF V600E on dependency_BRAF -0.555, EGFR amplification on dependency_EGFR -0.349, ERBB2 amplification on dependency_ERBB2 -0.432, KRAS mutation on dependency_KRAS -0.309, and NF1 loss on dependency_RIT1 -0.095; all were statistically significant. For KIF18A, an OLS model containing colorectal, APC mutation, high WNT, all lower-order interaction terms, growth, and Cas9 activity still estimated a strong negative three-way coefficient for colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT (coefficient -0.817; p=8.77e-228). This confirms that the KIF18A pattern is not explained by any one component alone.

Overall conclusions
Supported hypotheses: BRAF V600E -> BRAF dependency, EGFR amplification -> EGFR dependency, ERBB2 amplification -> ERBB2 dependency, KRAS mutation -> KRAS dependency, NF1 loss -> RIT1 dependency, MYC/8q24 context -> RPL11 dependency, and colorectal/APC-mutant/high-WNT context -> KIF18A dependency. The KIF18A subgroup is the strongest and most biologically specific noncanonical discovery in this dataset. Weaker or more exploratory patterns for TMED10 and DHX9 appear more tied to growth or screen context than to a single robust molecular subgroup. POLR2A is most strongly associated with growth rate, consistent with a broad proliferation-linked dependency rather than a driver-genotype-specific vulnerability.

 succeeded in 12274ms:
Dataset ds001_depmap contains 50000 cell-line records with 10 CRISPR dependency outcomes. I analyzed binary molecular features, categorical lineage/culture/batch variables, continuous molecular scores, and screen covariates. Dependency scores are interpreted on their natural scale, where more negative values mean stronger dependency.

Canonical driver dependencies were strongly recovered. `braf_v600e=1` predicted more negative `dependency_BRAF` (adjusted beta -0.5544; unadjusted means -0.8047 vs -0.2495, p approximately 1e-300). `egfr_amplification=1` predicted more negative `dependency_EGFR` (adjusted beta -0.3487; means -0.6010 vs -0.2524, p approximately 1e-300). `erbb2_amplification=1` predicted more negative `dependency_ERBB2` (adjusted beta -0.4325; means -0.6856 vs -0.2535, p approximately 1e-300). `kras_mutation=1` predicted more negative `dependency_KRAS` (adjusted beta -0.3088; means -0.5594 vs -0.2520, p approximately 1e-300).

Several lineage signals seen in the first scan were explained by driver enrichment rather than independent lineage biology. `lineage=skin` was no longer associated with `dependency_BRAF` after adjustment for `braf_v600e` (beta -0.0021, p=0.706). `lineage=brain` was null for `dependency_EGFR` after adjustment for `egfr_amplification` (beta 0.0029, p=0.635). `lineage=breast` and `lineage=gastric` were null in the adjusted ERBB2 model. The `kras_mutation` by `lineage=pancreatic` interaction was also null (beta -0.0004, p=0.971), supporting KRAS mutation itself rather than a pancreatic-specific KRAS-mutant dependency.

For RAS-pathway heterogeneity, `nf1_loss=1` was the clear RIT1-associated subgroup. `nf1_loss` lines had more negative `dependency_RIT1` scores than other lines (means -0.3527 vs -0.2572), and the association persisted after adjustment for growth and Cas9 activity (beta -0.0953, p approximately 1e-300).

The strongest noncanonical pattern was for `dependency_KIF18A`. Main-effect scans identified `lineage=colorectal`, `apc_mutation=1`, high `wnt_activity_score`, and high `rnaseq_ASCL2_log2_tpm` as related signals. Refinement showed that the complete dependency subgroup was `lineage=colorectal`, `apc_mutation=1`, high `wnt_activity_score` (`>=0.819`), and `smad4_loss=0`. This subgroup had mean `dependency_KIF18A` -1.2990 versus -0.2530 in all other lines (effect -1.0460, p approximately 1e-300). Within colorectal/APC/high-WNT lines, `smad4_loss=0` had mean -1.2990 while `smad4_loss=1` had mean -0.2557 (effect -1.0433, p approximately 1e-300), indicating that SMAD4 loss suppresses the otherwise strong KIF18A dependency.

MYC and chromosome 8q24 signals separated by outcome. Higher `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` independently predicted more negative `dependency_DHX9` (adjusted beta -0.0160, p approximately 1e-300), while `myc_amplification` itself was not independent after MYC expression was included. For `dependency_RPL11`, high `copy_number_8q24` was the independent signal (adjusted beta -0.1041, p approximately 1e-300); `myc_amplification` and `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm` were not independently negative once continuous 8q24 copy number was modeled.

`dependency_POLR2A` and `dependency_TMED10` were dominated by growth and screen covariates rather than a sharply defined molecular subgroup. Higher `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` strongly predicted more negative `dependency_POLR2A` (adjusted beta -0.3053, p approximately 1e-300) and more negative `dependency_TMED10` (adjusted beta -0.1010, p approximately 1e-300). `cas9_activity_score` was also negative in the TMED10 model (beta -0.1035, p=1.78e-15). `nf1_loss` had a small additional TMED10 association (beta -0.0134, p=0.013), but it was much weaker than the growth/Cas9 effects.

The systematic heterogeneity search covered every dependency outcome using binary predicates, categorical levels, upper/lower quartiles of continuous variables, and pair/triple subgroup intersections. Final best-supported subgroup definitions are: BRAF: `braf_v600e=1`; EGFR: `egfr_amplification=1`; ERBB2: `erbb2_amplification=1`; KRAS: `kras_mutation=1`; RIT1: `nf1_loss=1`; KIF18A: `lineage=colorectal`, `apc_mutation=1`, high `wnt_activity_score`, and `smad4_loss=0`; TMED10: primarily high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day` with a small `nf1_loss` component; DHX9: high `rnaseq_MYC_log2_tpm`; POLR2A: high `growth_rate_doublings_per_day`; RPL11: high `copy_number_8q24`, especially overlapping `myc_amplification`, with continuous 8q24 copy number carrying the independent effect.

